And if you don't have arbitrary skills... So I don't have... I'm not locked... You certainly...

36:16.889 --> 36:19.112
Do you have an antipathy to the computer?

36:19.152 --> 36:19.612
Yes, I do.

36:19.652 --> 36:26.381
I think, well, I've mentioned a number of examples through both Internet and World Wide Web, which I feel are bad for.

36:26.421 --> 36:27.783
I don't want to ruin my eyesight.

36:27.803 --> 36:28.904
You will notice what happens.

36:29.004 --> 36:31.007
Almost everybody who has a computer has glasses.

36:31.027 --> 36:32.008
Yeah, I don't have glasses yet.

36:32.028 --> 36:33.169
And I had a wonderful, perfect vision.

36:33.209 --> 36:34.331
A perfect vision until you have one.

36:34.391 --> 36:37.915
My father didn't wear glasses until he bought a computer at the age of 60 or something.

36:37.935 --> 36:40.438
I mean, I had fighter pilot eyes.

36:40.458 --> 36:41.159
I mean, I really did.

36:41.179 --> 36:42.221
I wasn't a fighter pilot.

36:42.241 --> 36:46.486
I was in the service because I had to be, but my vision was absolutely perfect.

36:46.526 --> 36:46.626
Yeah.

36:47.028 --> 36:50.152
And now it's, I can't, they're gone.

36:50.172 --> 36:52.114
Well, you see, I want to continue reading books.

36:52.815 --> 36:54.737
And I, you know, it's a ridiculous fact.

36:54.757 --> 37:10.757
I think this whole thing is a, you know, it's made speed up in work and it's destroyed not only Carpool Tunnel, but I, you also have to remember there's one important factor about computers that made them very easily acceptable to most people and not to myself, is that not having grown up with films or television, uh,

37:11.513 --> 37:14.258
To me, a screen has inadequate resolution.

37:14.418 --> 37:20.729
Indeed, much of modern offset printing is inadequate, but a good, solid letterpress is to my ideal resolution.

37:20.990 --> 37:23.214
I'm not used to seeing information on a screen.

37:23.494 --> 37:25.257
To me, it gives me a headache quite rapidly.

37:25.277 --> 37:26.940
Now, most people move from a television...

37:27.241 --> 37:29.204
screen to a computer screen just fine.

37:29.224 --> 37:35.854
I might find one of my objections to computers vanishing if there were some extremely high resolution non-screen.

37:35.994 --> 37:46.189
I think for the database material that you do, especially with all the stuff you put on cards and all the books you've read and all the footnotes, you know, computer technology there would be outstanding.

37:46.209 --> 37:46.609
Yeah, exactly.

37:46.649 --> 37:51.256
But on the other hand, I've started this, you know, I have to retrospectively do 30 years of reading.

37:51.336 --> 37:53.319
Retrospective conversion, they call it.

37:53.519 --> 37:56.083
Yeah, but it's all on his handwriting, not even typed.

37:56.215 --> 38:01.321
Retro, of course, retcon, Nichols and Bacon, I'm sure they've told you what a total fiasco is.

38:01.341 --> 38:03.243
These catalogs are no longer works of scholarship.

38:03.283 --> 38:06.047
The old Library of Congress cards, you could take those for gospel.

38:06.727 --> 38:13.976
These catalogs up here, it's making it easier for the library with budgetary cutbacks and stuff and harder for the person.

38:14.196 --> 38:19.342
You could look up something because it's never been done by anyone with brains.

38:19.683 --> 38:25.389
If they've got a book by Raphael Urciolo written down there, then they have a new one that they've got a catalog by R.G.

38:25.449 --> 38:26.070
Urciolo,

38:26.337 --> 38:29.281
Anyone who knows romance philology might tell you, well, R.G.

38:29.361 --> 38:36.630
Urciolo and Raphael Urciolo are the same person, but some poor hack who just knows how to work a computer doesn't know that, so you end up with two entries.

38:36.650 --> 38:39.514
And if somebody more accomplished, I mean, I've chosen a fairly researche name.

38:40.095 --> 38:44.080
If you've got something fairly complicated, you can find huge long lists.

38:44.100 --> 38:48.025
And if you want to find all the works of Benedetto Croce, for instance, you can spend...

38:48.393 --> 38:57.988
two hours looking through that catalog up there, whereas in the National Union catalog, you could take, you know, he's got a lot of pages because he wrote hundreds of books, but still it's manageable.

38:58.549 --> 39:02.495
And it's just, it's a way of shifting the labor onto someone else.

39:02.555 --> 39:04.799
And so many of these people have no sense of even how to use books.

39:05.119 --> 39:06.321
They can't even use computers.

39:07.042 --> 39:15.075
And I also, of course, a book, you know, well, this is old hat, you must, every computer, anti-computer person must tell you, hires unverified information out there.

39:15.292 --> 39:32.453
and people act as though they either decide, yes, they realize it's all unverified, therefore they assume something written by Nicholas Barker or John Sparrow is also unverified information, or they're used to reading Nicholas Barker, and they realize it's all gospel truth, and they transfer that to the Internet.

39:32.473 --> 39:36.338
I mean, either way, people don't have a critical... There's no editor.

39:38.420 --> 39:43.206
There's no way to distinguish between what's authentic, what's gone through the filtration process,

39:44.030 --> 39:46.013
Oh, it's very suspect.

39:46.033 --> 39:47.515
Listen, I'm going to get my car back.

39:47.816 --> 39:48.257
Okay.

39:48.277 --> 39:53.605
I will tell you in 30 seconds the last thing I meant to say, which is the Lasky quotation.

39:53.625 --> 39:58.172
He described how Lord Acton, you know, who had 100,000... Who's quotation again?

39:58.212 --> 40:00.696
This is Lasky's quotation of Lord Acton.

40:02.559 --> 40:06.966
It's obviously reported to Lasky because Acton died in 1901.

40:07.346 --> 40:08.929
That's what we did finish.

40:09.009 --> 40:09.109
Yeah.

40:09.815 --> 40:17.181
This is, I think, very significant not only to book collecting, to the Internet, hierarchy of information, organizing of information, scholarly practices.

40:17.782 --> 40:39.180
He said that Acton, the club, which is the club that's founded originally by Samuel Johnson, and it continues, with a small membership of fairly learning people, Acton, who, of course, had read everything, Acton would, in support of his opinions, which he had, he would quote, as I do, in fact,

40:39.515 --> 40:46.964
not only giving the work, footnoting, I mean, full documentation, he would quote authorities which his interlocutors did not know.

40:47.644 --> 40:57.376
And he was always vanquished in argument because they were unable to, they had no way of knowing whether the quotation that he gave was from a respectable book or not.

40:57.436 --> 41:02.602
Now, you could have taken it for granted that anything acted says comes from a source that may be taken as gospel, but they didn't know that.

41:02.622 --> 41:04.744
So that gets back to things like Printing of the Mind of Man.

41:05.024 --> 41:08.188
If you quote from Printing of the Mind of Man, it's a known entity.

41:08.523 --> 41:14.893
If you quote from something completely obscure, unless, I mean, people can quote from my catalogs who know me, and some of them occasionally do.

41:15.454 --> 41:18.719
But I realize, you know, there are 125 people in the world who have heard of me, and that's it.

41:18.739 --> 41:22.485
And to a small group, they will say, as Ian Jackson says, such and such.

41:22.525 --> 41:27.072
But to the rest, it's completely lost on them, and they have no idea whether I know what I'm talking about or not.

41:27.452 --> 41:28.774
And Acton's problem is the same way.

